Okay, here's a breakdown of each section of the bill, as requested.

**Sec. 90001. Border Infrastructure and Wall System.**

This section allocates $46.55 billion to U.S. Customs and Border Protection for border infrastructure projects. These projects include the construction, installation, or improvement of barriers (primary, waterborne, and secondary), access roads, and related technology like cameras, lights, and sensors. The funds are available until September 30, 2029, and also cover ground preparation work necessary for the barrier system.

**Sec. 90002. U.S. Customs and Border Protection Personnel, Fleet Vehicles, and Facilities.**

This section provides a total of $8.255 billion to U.S. Customs and Border Protection for personnel, retention bonuses, vehicles, and facilities. Specifically, $4.1 billion is for hiring and training additional agents and support personnel, $2.05 billion for recruitment and retention bonuses, $855 million for vehicle repair and acquisition, and $5 billion for facility improvements and construction.  A restriction prevents funds from being used to hire personnel specifically for processing coordinators after October 31, 2028.

**Sec. 90003. Detention Capacity.**

This section allocates $45 billion to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement for single adult and family detention capacity.  Aliens detained at family residential centers can be held pending immigration decisions or until removal, and detention standards for single adults are at the discretion of the Secretary of Homeland Security. The definition of "family residential center" is clarified to include facilities detaining family units, excluding unaccompanied children.

**Sec. 90004. Border Security, Technology, and Screening.**

This section provides $6.168 billion to U.S. Customs and Border Protection for border security enhancements. This includes procuring advanced inspection equipment with AI and machine learning, upgrading air and marine operations, improving surveillance technology, and implementing biometric entry/exit systems.  Funds cannot be used for surveillance towers along the border that lack tested autonomous capabilities.

**Sec. 90005. State and Local Assistance.**

This section provides funding for state and local security initiatives. $500 million is allocated to the State Homeland Security Grant Program for unmanned aircraft system threat detection, $625 million for security related to the 2026 FIFA World Cup, $1 billion for the 2028 Olympics, and $450 million for the Operation Stonegarden Grant Program.  Additionally, it establishes a "State Border Security Reinforcement Fund" with $10 billion to support border wall construction, detection of illicit substances, and relocation of unlawfully present aliens, with restrictions to prevent states from exceeding federal immigration authority.

**Sec. 90006. Presidential Residence Protection.**

This section allocates $300 million to the Federal Emergency Management Agency to reimburse state and local agencies for extraordinary law enforcement costs associated with protecting presidential residences.  The funds can only be used for costs exceeding typical operations, directly related to Secret Service protection, and certified as compensating protection activities. The FEMA may use not more than 3 percent of the funds for administrative purposes.

**Sec. 90007. Department of Homeland Security Appropriations for Border Support.**

This section provides an additional $10 billion to the Department of Homeland Security for reimbursement of costs related to supporting its border security mission. The funds are available until September 30, 2029.

**Sec. 90101. FEHB Improvements.**

This section, titled the "FEHB Protection Act of 2025," aims to improve verification processes within the Federal Employees Health Benefits (FEHB) program. It mandates the Office of Personnel Management to verify qualifying life events for enrollment and audit family member eligibility, and to develop a process for disenrolling ineligible individuals. It also increases funding for oversight and audit activities within the FEHB program.

**Sec. 90102. Pandemic Response Accountability Committee.**

This section provides $88 million to the Pandemic Response Accountability Committee to support oversight of pandemic-related spending. It also amends the CARES Act to include this Act in the list of covered legislation for oversight purposes and extends the oversight period to 2034.

**Sec. 90103. Appropriation for the Office of Management and Budget.**

This section allocates $100 million to the Office of Management and Budget to identify and implement budget and accounting efficiencies within the executive branch. The funds are available until September 30, 2029. [end of text]


